  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA231-kiḷavi">ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi colli varaivu kaṭāyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">The confidante urging for marriage, speaking while [HE] is behind the fence.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA231">
<l>            maiyaṟa viḷaṅkiya maṇiniṟa vicumpiṟ</l>
<l>            kaitoḻu marapi ṉeḻumīṉ pōlap</l>
<l>            peruṅkaṭaṟ parappi ṉirumpuṟan tōyac</l>
<l>            ciṟuveṇ kākkai palavuṭa ṉāṭun</l>
<l>            tuṟaipulam puṭaittē tōḻi paṇṭu </l>
<l>            muḷḷūrk kurīik karuvuṭait taṉṉa</l>
<l>            perumpō taviḻnta karuntāṭ puṉṉaik</l>
<l>            kāṉalaṅ koṇkaṉ ṟanta</l>
<l>            kāta ṉammoṭu nīṅkā māṟē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>The ghat,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the little white crows, many together, search,</l>
<l rend="indent3">so that [their] big backs get wet, the extension of the dark sea,</l>
<l rend="indent2">as the seven stars customarily worshipped in the sapphire-</l>
<l rend="indent2">coloured sky that have begun to shine</l>
<l rend="indent2">when the collyrium[-clouds] subside,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">maiyaṟa</term> may either refer to the dark clouds in the sky or to the flawless quality of the sapphire.</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">is full of loneliness, friend,</l>
<l rend="indent2">because the love</l>
<l rend="indent3">given by the man from the land of seashore groves</l>
<l rend="indent">with black-trunked Puṉṉai trees that have opened big buds</l>
<l rend="indent3">like the broken egg of the bird in the inner village, formerly,</l>
<l rend="indent4">does not stay behind with us.<note place="foot">Actually, <term xml:lang="ta">nammoṭu nīṅkā</term> presents a syntactical problem. nīṅku usually is a transitive verb, and it is used for something/someone that goes away from a place, "to leave". So we would expect just a nam, a direct object, and if that were the case one would be inclined to read the <term xml:lang="ta">nīṅkā</term> as a positive absolutive, since if HIS love has not left HER, why would the ghat be lonely? T.V.G. accordingly reads the nammoṭu as an accusative. Another possibility of construction is: "he doesn’t leave [his] love with us", and that might be even more likely, but in the translation it does not work with the tanta construction.</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
